stabilis rerum terminus] 111 using the phrase ‘abiding land- mark of our fortunes,’ Horace is clearly referring to the popular legend that, when space was being made for a temple of Jupiter on the Capitol, the god Terminus (see Class. Dict. s. v.) alone refused to make way, thus symbolizing the eternal stability of the Roman state.
